	(2098,503,'activities_7_activity_name','Interview 3: BBC 10 for John and Julian; ITV News at 10 for Ellen    '),
	(2099,503,'_activities_7_activity_name','field_5b11097814d45'),
	(2100,503,'activities_7_activity_description','Complex legal cases need careful explanations to a general audience; we will encourage the participants to get their outcomes delivered in short clips and with the intention of being easy to understand and memorable.\r\n\r\nWe will run a down-the-line scenario as well as some pre-rec clips. The coach will begin by talking through the set-up requirements of these types of interviews, and we will use the footage to analyse the success of the interview. Possible subjects include the Barclays trial, Brexit threat to cybersecurity, womens rights issues including FGM legislation and anything else thrown up by the news agenda of the day.'),
	(1552,404,'_overview','field_5b1023299fc62'),
	(1553,404,'went_well','<ul>\r\n 	<li>There were some important tips that we wanted to remind you of (and which you implemented well).\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Immediately express empathy</em></strong>when the issue of potential job cuts is mentioned.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Use a context setter </em></strong>to reboot the interview along more positive lines (e.g. by explaining the difference between the attitude of GE (peripheral) and ABB (core) towards electrical products.</li>\r\n 	<li>Stating that the assessment of various plants <em>is<strong>an ongoing process,</strong></em>and adding but we can promise to keep the lines of communication open and the employees fully informed at every stage.</li>\r\n 	<li>Countering second attempts by the interviewer to engage with a negative issue or speculation with a phrase like <strong><em>Well, as I said before ,</em></strong>and repeating your first response.</li>\r\n 	<li>The value of having approved, specific responses, such as The process is ongoing, but we will be able to give a decision within X months.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n 	<li>You did well to challenge the journalist on several occasions using phrasing like: I disagree with you on that. <strong><em>It is fine to politely disagree with the journalist</em></strong>. It sets up a dynamic in which you are assertive about delivering your messages and they are often grateful to have their facts corrected.However, you did go into a detailed explanation. Your answer would have been stronger if you had started with a simple <strong><em>no</em></strong> and then given the explanation.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Do not speculate</em></strong>. You became good at this, but need to keep it top of mind to avoid making statements you cannot deliver on for example protecting all the employees of GE.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>The narrative you delivered about the GE brand was powerful. </em></strong>The fact you may even rebrand some ABB products where GE has the stronger market recognition is excellent supportive evidence of your commitment to the GE business and be reassuring to your new colleagues.</li>\r\n 	<li>In your last townhall you did an excellent job of being engaging. Using <strong><em>you</em></strong>and <strong><em>talking from the audiences point of view</em></strong>will help the audience to listen to you, as will your use of rhetorical questions.We also liked your use of your own personal story to talk about ABB as a good employer.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Humour works, even with serious topics</em></strong>. You could see this when you talked about your head of HR having to spend many hours with you. It makes you come across with more authenticity and concern, rather than as a corporate mouthpiece.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(1554,404,'_went_well','field_5b21350c1cb97'),
	(1555,404,'more_work','<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>There needs to be congruency between what we see and what we hear?</em></strong>The audience will take meaning from how you deliver your messages. We like to see hands  and using gesture to add emphasis to important points. If you are trying to convince people that they are welcome to the ABB fold, you need to <strong>look </strong>happy about it.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Energy levels are important</em></strong>, especially when talking to large audiences. Moving around a stage helps to engage all of the audience. However, you need moments of stillness when you want to deliver key messages.</li>\r\n 	<li>It is important that <strong><em>you break up your messages</em></strong>, pausing in-between them, to give the audience the opportunity to absorb new information.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Negatives stick.</em></strong>The negative language in the question belongs to the questioner not you. For example, when you were asked if there is a problem, a response of there is no problem acts as reinforcement of the idea of a problem in the audiences mind, even though it is a denial.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>You need to sound inclusive rather than remote with all stakeholders.</em></strong>For example, when you talked about communications with local government officials you said you would inform them because you had to. It would be better to talk about them being included</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(1556,404,'_more_work','field_5b23849124c44'),
	(1557,404,'conclusions','Mike, we were impressed how well you assimilated the feedback. You will need to adapt your messages for the three locations and our strong recommendation is that the key to strong performance, both with media and in townhall type situations is rehearsal. Simply delivering your message out loud to a colleague before an interview or meeting, can eliminate mistakes and help you feel confident.\r\n\r\nThanks again for your time, we hope your journey out of London was less eventful than your flight to us. We would be delighted to work with you to support your team. Please do let us know when you would like to discuss this further.\r\n\r\nKind regards\r\nBen Shore and Sandra Davis'),
	(1558,404,'_conclusions','field_5b1023779fc64'),
