	(2477,547,'overview','Dear John,\r\n\r\nIt was good to meet you and thank you for your time and commitment during the recent media training session. We hope that you found the insight into the journalists agenda useful, and that you will be able to use some of the lessons learned in future engagements.\r\n\r\nIn this note, we capture the main feedback points from the session, where you performed well, and where there are areas to work on.\r\n\r\nWe recommend that you look back at your performances in the private portal we provide for you. Please click through the thumbnail on the portal.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Introduction</em></strong>\r\n\r\nIn the session, we focused on the broadcast media and simulated a radio from the perspective of the business slot on BBC Radio 4s Today programme and two TV interviews; a face-to-face studio interview with Ian King Live on Sky News and a clip for a package with BBC News. We believe this gives our clients relevant insight and experience of the different demands of each format so that you can prepare appropriately.'),
	(2478,547,'_overview','field_5b1023299fc62'),
	(2479,547,'went_well','<ul>\r\n 	<li>Good use of examples - even within the initial response in the first interview - when you talked about the devastating effect of injustice, when clients have done nothing wrong and the ruinous cost of having their accounts blocked. This positioned you as a firm which genuinely cares for and defends its clients.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Myddleton</strong>: John, you said, we cannot comment on specific cases, whereas commenting on cases where there is no client conflict is an essential profile-raising tool. You eloquently discussed the Proceeds of Crime Act and Unexplained Wealth Orders and we discussed the example of Zamira Hajiyeva who spent 16m in Harrods, and 1.2m on a diamond.\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>You did well to brand BCL Solicitors in every interview. This can come over as somewhat crass and cumbersome, but you were elegant and discreet about mentioning the name of the firm, particularly as you did so in relation to the actions you were taking to protect clients from injustice.</li>\r\n 	<li>You absorbed all the advice, adjusting your length of answer and delivering an excellent sound-bite in the BBC News interview, which could be used in isolation, without needing to include the reporters question. Ensuring that you repeat the part of the question with which you agree in this format helps in the editing process and increases your chances of being quoted.</li>\r\n 	<li>You are calm and collected, even when being asked a tricky question. This conveyed a dependable, competent and approachable demeanour, which will cause confidence and trust, causing people to look to BCL Solicitors for leadership and help.</li>\r\n 	<li>You were right to resist repeating the negative language of the questions, using your own vocabulary to redefine the context. This was particularly impressive in the case of the Ian King question about Phillip Green, BAE Systems briberydefending the indefensible, where you talked about the clients who need our help instead of indulging the dangerous words of the presenter.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(2480,547,'_went_well','field_5b21350c1cb97'),
	(2481,547,'more_work','<ul>\r\n 	<li>Tell us what is rather than what is not. In the first interview, you said, its not always about prosecution and lets think about it. We discussed how you can pick which part of a long question that you wish to answer and that which is of most value to you in achieving your objectives. Your advice to clients would have been the most worthwhile use of your time at the end of the first interview. Also, thinking is better done before a national broadcast interview, so that the two minutes available to you are used to maximum value.</li>\r\n 	<li>Cut out social qualifying words, such as quite which dilute the power of your argument. Being wrongly accused and locked out of your account is devastating, rather than quite devastating.</li>\r\n 	<li>Think bingo, rather than chess. Boil down the length of your answers by cutting out inessential words as above and also using examples from your own experience, to illustrate and humanise complex matters involving processes and data, which will be too much for the audience to digest in the short broadcast format.</li>\r\n 	<li>Be aware of your listening position. We discussed the importance of appearing to be pleased to be appearing, to lend your expertise on behalf of BCL Solicitors; in the first TV interview, you looked very serious, which can be misinterpreted as lack of confidence. People are more likely to listen to what you have to say and believe you, if you appear to be engaged and upbeat about what you are saying. Also, use gesture to avoid the fiddling with your fingers, which can betray your discomfort while listening to a tricky question.</li>\r\n 	<li>Wardrobe: Avoid the black and white combination, as the camera as the human eye, thus the colour will be drained out of your face to compensate. A light blue shirt and midnight blue jacket is a combination that the camera will love and will reward you for wearing.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(2482,547,'_more_work','field_5b23849124c44'),
	(2483,547,'conclusions','At the beginning of the session, we asked you about your personal brand and how you wanted to come across, you said:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Knowledgeable </em></strong> Yes, you achieved this from the start</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Clever </em></strong> Yes, notably by the BBC News interview when you spoke with measured pace and in the language of the target audience with a clear explanation of the risks and entrenching of bad attitudes</li>\r\n 	<li><strong><em>Approachable - </em></strong>Yes, you looked much happier to be speaking on behalf of BCL Solicitors by the last interview.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe key point is to build-in a preparation process in partnership with Myddleton ahead of all media engagements that allows you to identify your key messages and develop memorable proof points to support them. You have the style and gravitas to be an excellent media asset for BCL Solicitors.\r\n\r\nIf there is anything more Bladonmore can help with, please do not hesitate to get in contact with us through Paul, Deborah or Paula.\r\n\r\nKind regards,\r\nMatt Guarente and Susan Bookbinder'),
