	(4980,640,'overview','Thank you for your time, energy and enthusiasm in what we felt was a most constructive and worthwhile session. What follows is your formal feedback note. We divide it into what went well and areas to work on.\r\n\r\nWe recommend that you look back at the interviews and exercises on the portal, alongside this note. Our clients find it is a helpful reminder of the learning points in the session, as it causes further refinement of your desired media and personal brand.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Objectives</em></strong>\r\n\r\nAt the beginning of the session, we asked you to think about your personal brand and the impression that you would like to leave in the media as a representative of BCL.\r\n\r\nIn consultation with you and the team at Myddleton, we divided you into two groups relevant to your specialist <strong>practices</strong> and you were presented with various scenarios that were designed to align to your areas of expertise; A reaction to the SFOs recent actions against individuals and corporates, the recent rise in cyber-sex crime and calls by NSPCC for prosecutions against social media giants, briefings to a new journalist at Law 360 on the effect of Brexit on the European Arrest Warrant, a pitch to regional press on county lines crime, the effect of extra regulation on small food businesses and finally two press conferences in which the delegates alternated between showing a united front by fielding questions from journalists from a number of publications and asking their own questions of their colleagues. The latter exercise enabled you to develop skills that will be useful when presenting together on a public platform. You then faced tough questions from reporters from The Sun, The Daily Mail, The Telegraph, The Guardian, Computer Weekly and even FOI Magazine. The previous exercises ensured that each of you was provided with the opportunity to represent BCL Solicitors after having been briefed by their colleagues.\r\n\r\nWe interlaced advice on presentation skills and the importance of <u>total communication.</u> We presented insight into the psychology of journalists and how they are likely to behave against the demands of online rolling news deadlines and background of the newsroom hierarchy. We explained both the similarities and differences in print and broadcast media and how this would affect the delegates ability to get the BCL Solicitors message into the headlines. We offered advice and techniques on how delegates could best use this knowledge to help journalists get their story published, but on the terms prepared and considered using the Bladonmore IMEAN and FOAM systems, which would promote and protect the principles of BCL Solicitors.'),
	(4981,640,'_overview','field_5b1023299fc62'),
	(4982,640,'went_well','<ul>\r\n 	<li>You did well to maintain serenity whilst being asked difficult questions and being interrupted. This is important when your clients are looking to you for leadership and confidence. We deliberately give delegates some tough treatment in order to give them a realistic experience of how journalists behave in order to maintain and generate readership and their own brand.</li>\r\n 	<li>Ellen <strong>eloquently</strong> delivered the message, crafted alongside her group using the IMEAN system, that <strong>the extension of</strong> age-verification <strong>technology</strong> was a key move by the Culture Secretary to protect children using social media. We agreed that she could have helicoptered back to this key message to regain control when the interview wandered into the call for criminal sanctions against (BCLs client) Facebook. We advised that, whilst we understand the discomfort of this position, there is no reason that BCL Solicitors should not use its expertise to command greater authority in the mass media.</li>\r\n 	<li>John also used the IMEAN system in collaboration with his group, to give evocative insight into the pattern of SFO failures. John crafted evocative messages with skilful use of pithy, illustrative language; the wrong people pursued in the wrong way the suffering of wrongly-accused clients <strong>and the wrong use of taxpayers money.</strong></li>\r\n 	<li>Rachel brought energy to her exercises with dynamic use of gesture, and was robust in the press conference exercise, in which she powerfully positioned BCL Solicitors as a defender of due process and not that of the vigilante, when faced by two hardened reporters from The Sun! In the briefing of the Law 360 reporter, she was particularly impressive in using the Bladonmore <em>FOAM </em>system to deliver <em>facts</em> (10 thousand foreign offenders), <em>metaphor</em> (the jails full of Polish cabbage thieves) and <em>observation</em> (champagne corks all over Europe). Rachel is also very easy on the ear.</li>\r\n 	<li>Shula was adept at using her <em>observation</em> of the recruitment underway at CPS in her Brexit interview with Law 360. This would have reassured the journalist that she was talking to the right person, who not only had an inside track (she <em>evidenced</em> the insight with her knowledge of Max Hill) but also <em>front-loaded</em> a considered headline, that a no-deal would/will be a disaster.</li>\r\n 	<li>Paul also used the technique of <em>front-loading</em> to take immediate control of the pitch to the editor of the Coventry Evening Telegraph, using the <em>fact</em> that <strong>46 ,000 </strong>were affected. This set the scene for the local detail the editor is hunting; a 42% rise in West Mercia. Having seized the interest of the editor with these local facts, he went on to use the language of the target audience (the children used as mules) to explain how the hands of the police are tied, due to the age of criminal responsibility.</li>\r\n 	<li>Richard absorbed all the advice, offering the local detail of the small business on the high street faced with bankruptcy because of over-regulation. He did well to back up the claims with the <em>facts</em> that 60% of small businesses simply will not be able to afford it. Richard was also impressive in stepping in to support John in the press conference on the matter of cyber security measures already in practice. <strong>Myddleton: Richard, you would do well to try and sound empathetic when questioned about a death, as well as explaining the ill effects of draconian regulation.</strong></li>\r\n 	<li>Julian was an excellent chair in the press conference exercise, showing both leadership and solidarity with his BCL Solicitors colleagues, in particular when faced with a rather nasty question from The Daily Mail in the form of Richard who argued that he would have blood on your hands re Instagram! He also stepped in to show solidarity with Ellen on the Brexit question from The Guardian, correctly pointing out that it is for the government to govern and for BCL Solicitors to seek justice for all.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(4983,640,'_went_well','field_5b21350c1cb97'),
	(4984,640,'more_work','<ul>\r\n 	<li>Tell us what is, rather than what is not. If you cant answer a loaded question about a second referendum or general election, acknowledge the question by stating that it is a matter for the House of Commons to decide and move to your prepared, planned position to avoid being trapped on the agenda of the journalist, which is of no use to your communications strategy.</li>\r\n 	<li>Be aware of your listening positon. Mouth movements, when listening to a tricky question can betray your discomfort. Similarly, smiling or nodding whilst listening to a question about BCL supporting paedophiles for example can indicate agreement.</li>\r\n 	<li>Having developed important content to reassure customers that BCL represents people who are wrongly-accused, you cannot rely on the journalist to prompt you to deliver it. Front-load this material to transition from the journalists negative agenda, to your own prepared and positive strategy.</li>\r\n 	<li>Do not take sweets from strangers; do not repeat negative words from interviewers. So, if you feel that the SFO is not a disaster, what is it?</li>\r\n 	<li>Slow down. Briefing a ranting news editor or deadline-driven journalist can infect your pace of delivery. Control comes from slowing the pace, emphasising and repeating your key points.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
	(4985,640,'_more_work','field_5b23849124c44'),
	(4986,640,'conclusions','It was a great pleasure to meet/see and work with you all on this session. We would like to thank everyone for engaging with the exercises, taking on board our advice and acting upon our suggested preparation and interview techniques. With further consultation with Myddleton, we are sure that all of you will be valuable print media representatives of BCL Solicitors.'),
